<div id="review_1187692694" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1187692694" />
    <a title="Carolyn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19559507-carolyn"><img alt="Carolyn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546411572p2/19559507.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1187692694?book_show_action=true">Dec 19, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carolyn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carolyn" href="/user/show/19559507-carolyn">Carolyn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6318821-half-of-a-yellow-sun">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19559507-carolyn?shelf=historical">historical</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19559507-carolyn?shelf=war">war</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1187692694" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11076653211477756935">It would be easy to write a long review about this fascinating book but there are already so many excellent reviews by more able reviewers that I will keep my comments brief.<br/><br/>Although I was aware of the Biafran war and the mass starvation and death that resulted, I never had any understanding of the reasons leading to the birth of Biafra and the aftermath of it&apos;s Denise. Through her gentle but effective prose, Adichie has opened my eyes to the role colonialism has had (not just in Nigeria but all</span>
  <span id="freeText11076653211477756935" style="display:none">It would be easy to write a long review about this fascinating book but there are already so many excellent reviews by more able reviewers that I will keep my comments brief.<br /><br />Although I was aware of the Biafran war and the mass starvation and death that resulted, I never had any understanding of the reasons leading to the birth of Biafra and the aftermath of it's Denise. Through her gentle but effective prose, Adichie has opened my eyes to the role colonialism has had (not just in Nigeria but all over Africa) in trying to force disparate tribes into unified countries. When Britain amalgamated Southern Nigeria and Northern Nigeria into a single country in 1914, they failed to take into account the very different cultures of the people - the wealthy, well educated, democratically organised Christian and animist Igbo people in the south west, the Yoruba in the South East and the Islamic Hausa and Fulani peoples ruled by Emirs in the North. Ongoing friction, an attempted coup and persecution of the Igbo in the northern states eventually led to the secession of the Igbo lands into the new nation they called Biafra, their flag half of a yellow sun on a background of black and green.<br /><br />Adichie skillfully takes us through the events leading up to the Biafran war through the eyes of two wealthy sisters, Olanna and Kainene and their lovers, the University academic and revolutionist Odenigbo and the British writer Richard Churchill as well as Odenigbo's house boy Ugwu, a young Igbo villager. Through them we see the gradual collapse of their society and wealth, their struggle to survive through the war and the realisation of what it has cost them in the aftermath. Powerfully written in quite simple yet potent prose, with patches of humour even in the worst of times, this is a very accomplished work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11076653211477756935" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


